{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\nThe auto-lander is a long-running service; it must deploy like the review-bot and log to its OWN service logs — writing to `session_log` would blur that type's purpose (it is for agentic sessions, not CI/infra processes).\n\n## What\nContainerize the service and wire it into docker-compose (single instance) on the existing Gerrit box; route logs to container stdout → the existing CloudWatch monitoring.\n\n## Dependencies\nDepends on **S2** (`perovskite-frilly-grebe`, 0ee8-08de-bf0f-45ec) — the core loop: this story packages and deploys the loop service, so there must be a service to containerize; the deploy is otherwise independent of the failure/command stories.\n\n## Scope\nDeploy + observability + single-instance guard. Not the loop logic.\n\n## Files\nNew files:\n- `infra/compose/Dockerfile.autolander` — service image + `HEALTHCHECK`.\n- `infra/terraform/monitoring_autolander.tf` — the `autolander_errors` alarm.\n\nExisting files edited:\n- `infra/compose/docker-compose.yml` — add the `autolander` compose service (single instance).\n- `infra/terraform/ssm.tf` — add the `/rebar/prod/autolander-gerrit-token` SecureString param.\n- `infra/scripts/fetch-secrets.sh` — fetch the autolander Gerrit token at boot.\n- `infra/scripts/observability.sh` — add the `autolander_errors` `PutMetricData` feeders.\n\nRead-only / unchanged (referenced, not edited): `infra/terraform/iam.tf` — its existing `ssm_params_read` grant on the `rebar/prod/*` prefix already covers the token path, so NO IAM change is needed. Operator cutover (not a repo file): the `All-Projects` `refs/meta/config` capability grant (`rebaseOnBehalfOfUploader` + submit on `refs/heads/*`).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `infra/compose/Dockerfile.autolander` (new) + a compose service added to the existing `infra/compose/docker-compose.yml`.\n- [ ] **Single-instance guard:** the container acquires a POSIX advisory **file lock** (`flock` on a lockfile in its state volume) on start; a second copy fails to acquire it and exits. This `flock` is the **sole** single-instance mechanism — do NOT rely on `deploy.replicas: 1` (a Swarm-only key silently ignored by plain `docker compose`).\n- [ ] **Credentials (AC2 mechanism):** `autolander-bot`/RebarBotNava's `rebaseOnBehalfOfUploader` is a **server-level capability** granted in `All-Projects` `refs/meta/config` (`[capability]` / service-user grant), not a per-project label ACL; plus submit permission on `refs/heads/*`. The Gerrit HTTP token is provisioned as an SSM **SecureString** at the concrete path `/rebar/prod/autolander-gerrit-token` — inside the existing `parameter/rebar/prod/*` prefix that the EC2 instance-role IAM policy (`iam.tf` `ssm_params_read`) already grants, so NO IAM change is needed (a `/rebar/autolander/*` path would fall outside that grant) — added in `infra/terraform/ssm.tf`, fetched by `infra/scripts/fetch-secrets.sh`; never inlined.\n- [ ] **Observability (AC3):** logs go to container stdout; `infra/scripts/observability.sh` publishes the single `rebar/host:autolander_errors` metric (`PutMetricData`) from BOTH feeders — the `AUTOLANDER_ERROR` journald marker AND the container's `unhealthy` state (grepped on `CONTAINER_NAME=compose-autolander-1`) — one metric, two feeders, with an alarm in `infra/terraform/monitoring_autolander.tf`. The service NEVER writes `session_log`.\n- [ ] **Liveness/restart (AC4):** a `HEALTHCHECK` in `Dockerfile.autolander` marks the container `unhealthy` on a **hang** (a plain `restart: unless-stopped` only fires on process EXIT, not a hang); the compose service + an autoheal/`restart: unless-stopped` recreate it on exit/unhealthy, and the `unhealthy` state feeds the same `autolander_errors` metric named in AC3. (The `wipChain`-timeout parking of a stuck stack is loop logic owned by S2/S3, not this deploy story.)\n- [ ] **Heartbeat (AC5):** the bot writes a **heartbeat** — a timestamp file in the state volume (or a health metric) — on **every poll** iteration, i.e. once per the bot's **15 s poll interval** (S2's loop cadence), so under normal operation the heartbeat is never older than ~15 s and a stale one means the bot is down/wedged. **Contract (design-fixed):** heartbeat freshness ≤ 15 s; S4's `lander_down` treats a heartbeat **older than 90 s** (6× the poll) as down. This heartbeat (its location + the 90 s staleness threshold) is the interface contract S4's `lander_down` outcome reads.\n- [ ] **Queue-status surface (AC6):** emit a small queue-status surface exposing the current `wipChain` (change, phase, `tested_sha`, time-in-phase), the count of `Autosubmit`-set-and-waiting changes, and a **queue-wait / time-to-land histogram** metric with **design-fixed bucket boundaries of 30 s, 1 m, 2 m, 5 m, 10 m, 20 m, 30 m, 1 h** (in seconds: 30, 60, 120, 300, 600, 1200, 1800, 3600) — spanning a green fast-forward landing (~1–2 min for the CI re-run on the rebased patchset) through a heavily-contended `N=5` re-drive, so p50/p90/p99 time-to-land are readable — for debuggability and to validate the success criterion.\n- [ ] **Emergency-stop + drain (AC7):** an **emergency-stop** sentinel (a sentinel file / config flag the poll loop checks) transitions the bot to a `paused` state that STOPS consuming `Autosubmit` (for when `main` is on fire). **Drain-on-shutdown:** on redeploy/SIGTERM, finish the current `wipChain`, ack its outcome, then exit — so a redeploy never strands a half-processed stack."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783784535722291001,"uuid":"4ed8e7d2-256c-4b85-97e2-115cf28662b7"}